1
00:00:00,359 --> 00:00:05,750
In my experience watching the charts, I noticed
that during a downtrend, the price usually

2
00:00:05,750 --> 00:00:08,940
hits a point where it doesn't want to drop
any more.

3
00:00:08,940 --> 00:00:14,160
And if there's a very high volume bar at this
point of support, it could be a sign that

4
00:00:14,160 --> 00:00:16,740
the decline is ready to reverse.

5
00:00:16,740 --> 00:00:21,650
When I see a huge spike in volume, I know
something important must be happening in the

6
00:00:21,650 --> 00:00:22,650
market.

7
00:00:22,650 --> 00:00:28,370
A lot of volume means many traders are interested
in that part of the chart and are buying or

8
00:00:28,370 --> 00:00:29,840
selling there.

9
00:00:29,840 --> 00:00:34,700
It makes me curious - why are so many people
trading at this price?

10
00:00:34,700 --> 00:00:41,180
I said many times, sometimes analyzing charts
can be confusing if you just look at one thing

11
00:00:41,180 --> 00:00:44,070
like price action or volume alone.

12
00:00:44,070 --> 00:00:50,050
By watching what the price does after that
big volume bar, you can get indications about

13
00:00:50,050 --> 00:00:54,920
what the traders who caused it are trying
to do.

14
00:00:54,920 --> 00:01:00,219
While I was researching about using volume
in combination with price action, I came across

15
00:01:00,219 --> 00:01:02,430
the term "stopping volume."

16
00:01:02,430 --> 00:01:08,320
It's when the volume suddenly spikes really
big and stops the price from going down anymore.

17
00:01:08,320 --> 00:01:13,659
And this is exactly that very big volume bar
I see sometimes after a market has been falling

18
00:01:13,659 --> 00:01:15,740
or increasing for a while.

19
00:01:15,740 --> 00:01:21,950
It seems the big traders are using those moments
to go against the trend and start buying when

20
00:01:21,950 --> 00:01:26,659
the price is low, or start selling when the
price is high.

21
00:01:26,659 --> 00:01:29,260
Signals like this don't happen all the time.

22
00:01:29,260 --> 00:01:34,399
There's lots of ways people combine volume
and price action, but focusing on extreme

23
00:01:34,399 --> 00:01:39,229
volume spikes seems to give one of the best
signals.

24
00:01:39,229 --> 00:01:43,840
When one of those very high volume bars show
up, it changes everything.

25
00:01:43,840 --> 00:01:49,340
The price either levels out instead of keep
falling, or it even starts trending the other

26
00:01:49,340 --> 00:01:50,340
way.

27
00:01:50,340 --> 00:01:55,549
This can be explained by the fact that smart
money saw a chance to buy from everyone who

28
00:01:55,549 --> 00:01:57,799
was selling in a panic.

29
00:01:57,799 --> 00:02:02,969
And watching for signals like this will help
you to recognize when "smart money" is getting

30
00:02:02,969 --> 00:02:06,920
into or out of a market.

31
00:02:06,920 --> 00:02:12,220
One thing I've noticed about volume is that
it often predicts what will happen with the

32
00:02:12,220 --> 00:02:15,830
price better than looking just at the price
alone.

33
00:02:15,830 --> 00:02:22,720
It gives early signs of whether an uptrend
or downtrend is likely to keep going or might

34
00:02:22,720 --> 00:02:25,090
reverse direction soon.

35
00:02:25,090 --> 00:02:28,870
This is related to Wyckoff's law of effort
versus result.

36
00:02:28,870 --> 00:02:34,550
It's the idea that if the volume isn't matching
how much the price is moving, that could mean

37
00:02:34,550 --> 00:02:38,080
momentum is about to change.

38
00:02:38,080 --> 00:02:44,590
So when volume seems high compared to the
little moves in price, it catches my attention.

39
00:02:44,590 --> 00:02:50,300
Sometimes when I see volume changing before
the price, I know a reversal could be near.

40
00:02:50,300 --> 00:02:56,060
Like after a market has gone up a lot, if
the volume stays high while the price just

41
00:02:56,060 --> 00:03:04,159
goes sideways and can't break past old highs,
it makes me think the uptrend might be over.

42
00:03:04,159 --> 00:03:10,519
There's this volume indicator I use to show
if volume is high or low compared to the average.

43
00:03:10,519 --> 00:03:13,250
It's called volume spread for VSA.

44
00:03:13,250 --> 00:03:18,150
With it, I can easily spot the candles that
have very high volume.

45
00:03:18,150 --> 00:03:25,080
When you see red on the volume, something
important is happening under the surface.

46
00:03:25,080 --> 00:03:31,189
When I see one of those huge volume spikes
after prices have been falling, I start wondering

47
00:03:31,189 --> 00:03:33,280
what usually happens next.

48
00:03:33,280 --> 00:03:39,239
In an ideal scenario, it means the downtrend
is over at least for now.

49
00:03:39,239 --> 00:03:44,060
Sometimes that very high volume bar marks
the beginning of an up move.

50
00:03:44,060 --> 00:03:49,939
And I bet a lot of traders who were expecting
the downward to continue were caught on the

51
00:03:49,939 --> 00:03:51,409
wrong side.

52
00:03:51,409 --> 00:03:53,629
Of course, you have to be realist.

53
00:03:53,629 --> 00:03:58,799
Prices don't always turn right away - the
volume spike can also push the market into

54
00:03:58,799 --> 00:04:06,290
moving sideways in a range for a while instead
of continuing down or up.

55
00:04:06,290 --> 00:04:12,590
There's also a chance the declining trend
might keep going even after the big volume

56
00:04:12,590 --> 00:04:13,590
signal.

57
00:04:13,590 --> 00:04:19,660
That would show the sellers still have a lot
of power driving it down.

58
00:04:19,660 --> 00:04:25,590
That's why when I see one of those extreme
volume bars, I draw a channel around it to

59
00:04:25,590 --> 00:04:28,210
see how the price reacts.

60
00:04:28,210 --> 00:04:33,650
Then I only enter if it starts moving higher
or lower from that range.

61
00:04:33,650 --> 00:04:41,120
That helps filter out the bad trades where
price stops moving after the signal.

62
00:04:41,120 --> 00:04:47,090
When I see a candlestick that hasn't moved
prices much but still has regular volume,

63
00:04:47,090 --> 00:04:48,720
that makes sense to me.

64
00:04:48,720 --> 00:04:54,030
But when one of those small range candles
suddenly has super high volume, then it gets

65
00:04:54,030 --> 00:04:55,680
my attention.

66
00:04:55,680 --> 00:05:01,130
Something like a red down candle where the
prices didn't change much from open to close,

67
00:05:01,130 --> 00:05:04,600
but volume spiked way up - that's unusual.

68
00:05:04,600 --> 00:05:06,060
And in a good way.

69
00:05:06,060 --> 00:05:12,830
It's going against common sense because usually
high volume means a big move up or down.

70
00:05:12,830 --> 00:05:19,580
But in this case, even though volume exploded,
prices didn't drop further.

71
00:05:19,580 --> 00:05:26,039
According to Wyckoff's law, the effort (volume)
and result (price movement) aren't matching

72
00:05:26,039 --> 00:05:27,039
up.

73
00:05:27,039 --> 00:05:32,530
To me, that indicates sellers are meeting
more resistance at that level and it's getting

74
00:05:32,530 --> 00:05:36,120
harder for prices to fall below it.

75
00:05:36,120 --> 00:05:41,520
Candlestick patterns like that make me think
the decline could be running out of steam.

76
00:05:41,520 --> 00:05:48,860
It works both ways too - if there's an upwards
green candle with hugely high volume but prices

77
00:05:48,860 --> 00:05:55,400
didn't shoot up that much, it tells me something
different is happening under the surface.

78
00:05:55,400 --> 00:06:01,009
When buyers push volume through the roof but
the range stays small, it looks to me like

79
00:06:01,009 --> 00:06:06,349
sellers are stepping in more at that level
to balance things out.

80
00:06:06,349 --> 00:06:09,970
It's the first hint the upward momentum could
be fading.

81
00:06:09,970 --> 00:06:16,830
Again, just one signal like that isn't enough
- I need to see what prices do after to know

82
00:06:16,830 --> 00:06:19,960
if it really means a trend change is starting.

83
00:06:19,960 --> 00:06:25,729
If the price breaks below that big volume
candle in the future, that would confirm to

84
00:06:25,729 --> 00:06:30,970
me it's time to short sell, since the bulls
aren't in control anymore.

85
00:06:30,970 --> 00:06:35,940
There are 2 ways to trade this very high volume.

86
00:06:35,940 --> 00:06:40,100
To fade the move, or to trade a continuation.

87
00:06:40,100 --> 00:06:42,740
And that depends on the time frame you’re
trading.

88
00:06:42,740 --> 00:06:48,630
I’ve briefly talked about high volume bars
in a past video, and I used to scalp the 1-min

89
00:06:48,630 --> 00:06:49,819
chart with them.

90
00:06:49,819 --> 00:06:52,120
And it’s still a valid approach.

91
00:06:52,120 --> 00:06:58,110
But lately, I’m more inclined to swing trading,
and I had to adjust the method.

92
00:06:58,110 --> 00:07:04,039
The goal is watching how volume interacts
with price and recognizing the early warning

93
00:07:04,039 --> 00:07:10,400
signs like abnormal volume candles before
the trend turns.

94
00:07:10,400 --> 00:07:16,740
So here's how I would explain it from my perspective:
The strategy focuses on capitalizing when

95
00:07:16,740 --> 00:07:20,160
I see one of those massive volume spikes.

96
00:07:20,160 --> 00:07:25,240
It usually works like this:
The price has been falling or rising

97
00:07:25,240 --> 00:07:31,500
Then all of a sudden volume surges way up,
with a huge red volume candle

98
00:07:31,500 --> 00:07:36,920
Then I draw a box around the high and low
of that ultra high volume candle

99
00:07:36,920 --> 00:07:44,800
There are 2 scenarios: that big influx of
trading stops the previous momentum and price

100
00:07:44,800 --> 00:07:46,120
reverses.

101
00:07:46,120 --> 00:07:52,360
Or price continues in the initial direction
more aggressively than before.

102
00:07:52,360 --> 00:07:58,210
If I see prices bounce off that volume candle
and cross back into the box I drew, and breaks

103
00:07:58,210 --> 00:08:03,090
on the other side, that's my signal to jump
in with a buy order.

104
00:08:03,090 --> 00:08:08,990
My stop loss goes below the bottom of the
volume candle box, to protect myself in case

105
00:08:08,990 --> 00:08:10,770
price reverses.

106
00:08:10,770 --> 00:08:17,120
And the first target is to take profits when
I've made at least twice what I risked.

107
00:08:17,120 --> 00:08:22,770
Sometimes these volume signals launch bigger
moves, so there's potential for more gains

108
00:08:22,770 --> 00:08:23,900
too.

109
00:08:23,900 --> 00:08:29,120
So the first strategy is about fading the
move that just happened on the chart using

110
00:08:29,120 --> 00:08:31,770
the volume spike as my guide.

111
00:08:31,770 --> 00:08:35,840
The second strategy is a continuation of that
move.

112
00:08:35,840 --> 00:08:41,210
If I see that price continues in the initial
trend direction, that's my signal to jump

113
00:08:41,210 --> 00:08:45,810
in with a sell order, once price returns to
the box.

114
00:08:45,810 --> 00:08:51,180
I usually don’t sell right after the breakout,
although it’s a valid aggressive strategy.

115
00:08:51,180 --> 00:08:54,750
I usually wait for a retest of the box.

116
00:08:54,750 --> 00:08:56,870
My stop loss goes above box.

117
00:08:56,870 --> 00:09:01,190
And the same first target: at least twice
what I risked.

118
00:09:01,190 --> 00:09:06,390
So the second strategy is about trading a
continuation move, the volume spike adding

119
00:09:06,390 --> 00:09:09,459
fuel to the momentum.

120
00:09:09,459 --> 00:09:15,370
I notice EUR futures has been trading in a
range for a couple of weeks, and then started

121
00:09:15,370 --> 00:09:17,150
dropping again.

122
00:09:17,150 --> 00:09:23,649
Right as it was approaching this demand level,
volume suddenly spiked way up not just once

123
00:09:23,649 --> 00:09:28,320
but twice, second time with a small red candle.

124
00:09:28,320 --> 00:09:33,720
Those very high volume spikes at demand, after
the decline, caught my eye.

125
00:09:33,720 --> 00:09:38,529
Plus the signal price bar had a tight range
even with the high trading.

126
00:09:38,529 --> 00:09:43,010
So I drew a box around that area.

127
00:09:43,010 --> 00:09:48,839
Following the plan we discussed about fading
volume spikes, if EURO price breaks above

128
00:09:48,839 --> 00:09:53,079
the top of my box, that's when I'll hit the
buy button.

129
00:09:53,079 --> 00:09:58,160
My stop goes below demand just in case it
continues falling.

130
00:09:58,160 --> 00:10:02,620
And take profit once it reaches the next major
swing highs.

131
00:10:02,620 --> 00:10:10,010
This was the Daily time frame, so the strategy
is perfect if you have limited time for trading.

132
00:10:10,010 --> 00:10:14,240
If you’re day trading, there will be tons
of huge volume bars that pop up.

133
00:10:14,240 --> 00:10:20,400
But don't try trading each one - focus on
volume spikes that really stand out, especially

134
00:10:20,400 --> 00:10:23,260
near supply and demand levels.

135
00:10:23,260 --> 00:10:30,620
Like this one - we had an up move, then volume
exploded on a small red candle at the high.

136
00:10:30,620 --> 00:10:37,959
If it breaks below the low of our box, a sell
trade with a tight stop, targeting this swing

137
00:10:37,959 --> 00:10:41,930
low looks pretty good.

138
00:10:41,930 --> 00:10:45,260
Here I noticed another potential setup forming.

139
00:10:45,260 --> 00:10:50,810
It looks like a double bottom pattern with
an ultra high volume bar on this candle.

140
00:10:50,810 --> 00:10:57,839
So if it breaks above the top of that candle
after volume surged, I'll take the long entry.

141
00:10:57,839 --> 00:11:00,800
Stop loss under the recent swing low.

142
00:11:00,800 --> 00:11:05,570
And I'll aim to cash out when it hits the
next major high point - that should offer

143
00:11:05,570 --> 00:11:08,709
a very good profit target.

144
00:11:08,709 --> 00:11:14,840
In this example, I noticed a huge spike in
volume with a big green candle.

145
00:11:14,840 --> 00:11:21,149
Since the price range was also large from
open to close, it wasn't displaying the "effort

146
00:11:21,149 --> 00:11:25,490
vs result" imbalance we looked for in the
previous examples.

147
00:11:25,490 --> 00:11:33,070
With high volume matching a strong move up,
my impression was this likely signals a continuation

148
00:11:33,070 --> 00:11:36,690
of the trend rather than reversal potential.

149
00:11:36,690 --> 00:11:38,490
And that is our second approach.

150
00:11:38,490 --> 00:11:43,060
We are trading continuation moves after high
volume spikes.

151
00:11:43,060 --> 00:11:48,680
I drew a box around the signal candle, hoping
for an upward breakout.

152
00:11:48,680 --> 00:11:53,910
As I initially thought, price consolidated
just above the channel I made.

153
00:11:53,910 --> 00:11:59,589
So while this volume spike wasn't an optimal
"stopping volume" setup, observing it helped

154
00:11:59,589 --> 00:12:03,160
reinforce the previous bullish momentum.

155
00:12:03,160 --> 00:12:09,089
As a side note, in case price broke lower,
we could have taken a short trade at the retest

156
00:12:09,089 --> 00:12:10,740
of the box.

157
00:12:10,740 --> 00:12:14,589
Here another trend continuation signal.

158
00:12:14,589 --> 00:12:19,070
Prices had been declining and volume spiked
on a big candle.

159
00:12:19,070 --> 00:12:24,750
With high volume matching the strong down
move, this likely signals a continuation of

160
00:12:24,750 --> 00:12:25,750
the trend.

161
00:12:25,750 --> 00:12:29,320
A box was drawn around the high volume candle.

162
00:12:29,320 --> 00:12:36,180
Since the move down wasn't reversed after
the volume spike, this indeed signaled continuation

163
00:12:36,180 --> 00:12:37,470
of the downtrend.

164
00:12:37,470 --> 00:12:44,060
If prices will retest the bottom of the box
after the initial break lower, a short trade

165
00:12:44,060 --> 00:12:48,699
could be taken aiming for the next swing low.

166
00:12:48,699 --> 00:12:50,660
Another trend continuation signal.

167
00:12:50,660 --> 00:12:56,510
An upward move was underway when volume exploded
on a big green candle.

168
00:12:56,510 --> 00:13:03,250
This suggested buyers were actively testing
that resistance or supply level, indicating

169
00:13:03,250 --> 00:13:05,310
continued buying momentum.

170
00:13:05,310 --> 00:13:10,520
A long trade could be taken after a breakout
above the box drawn around the high volume

171
00:13:10,520 --> 00:13:16,650
candle, with a stop below and profit target
at the next swing high.

172
00:13:16,650 --> 00:13:17,650
Another signal.

173
00:13:17,650 --> 00:13:23,070
A large green candle appeared with matching
high trading volume.

174
00:13:23,070 --> 00:13:30,709
Since effort matched result signaling a strong
move, this pointed to further uptrend continuation

175
00:13:30,709 --> 00:13:31,949
rather than reversal.

176
00:13:31,949 --> 00:13:36,709
So we’re watching for an upward breakout
after price consolidation, and we are betting

177
00:13:36,709 --> 00:13:43,320
that existing bullish momentum will continue,
aiming to ride the trend higher.

178
00:13:43,320 --> 00:13:49,650
Of course, alternatively, a short could be
taken on a retest of the box if prices reversed

179
00:13:49,650 --> 00:13:51,200
its direction.

180
00:13:51,200 --> 00:13:54,490
You just have to be flexible and adaptable.

181
00:13:54,490 --> 00:14:01,839
Now, the market can be noisy, so focusing
on times when trading activity is highest

182
00:14:01,839 --> 00:14:06,160
helps reduce false signals from quiet periods.

183
00:14:06,160 --> 00:14:14,079
Signals seem most reliable for me during key
session overlaps, like London to New York.

184
00:14:14,079 --> 00:14:19,899
Signals formed when volume is normally low,
like overnight, haven't worked as well from

185
00:14:19,899 --> 00:14:21,140
what I've seen.

186
00:14:21,140 --> 00:14:27,509
And for stocks, the first 30 minutes after
open can be choppy.

187
00:14:27,509 --> 00:14:33,250
It helps to wait for volatility to settle
before entering, since that opening surge

188
00:14:33,250 --> 00:14:39,490
of volume can often be misleading
And most importantly, looking for spikes near

189
00:14:39,490 --> 00:14:46,120
evident levels of supply/demand, Fib levels,
VWAP or moving averages.

190
00:14:46,120 --> 00:14:58,619
These areas have the cleanest signals.

